      <p>
        The PROXXON Pen Sander PS 13 (Article No. 28594) is a superfine
        sander with a <em>linear</em> sanding stroke &mdash; the head moves up
        and down rather than rotating. It is held like a ballpoint pen and is
        designed for finishing surfaces in recesses, slots, compartments, and
        small corners: anywhere that is too tight for a conventional sander.
      </p>

      <h2>Specifications</h2>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Type</th><td>Superfine pen sander, linear (reciprocating) stroke</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Voltage</th><td>12&ndash;18 V DC</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Power</th><td>Approx. 10 W</td></tr>
          <tr><th>No. of strokes</th><td>8,000 / min</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Noise level</th><td>= 70 dB(A)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Supply cable</th><td>Spiral cable, approx. 100 cm, with reverse-polarity-protected connector</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Power supply (min.)</th><td>12&ndash;18 V DC at a minimum of 1 A</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Recommended supplies</th><td>PROXXON NG 2 (S/E) or NG 5/E power supply units</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Grinding inserts</th><td>Four straight + four angled inserts with differently shaped surfaces</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Sandpaper included</th><td>Self-adhesive, waterproof sheets in grain 180, 240, and 400 (5 &times; 4 pre-stamped shapes per sheet)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="note">
        For operation the PS 13 requires a DC supply of 12&ndash;18 V at a
        minimum of 1 A. PROXXON recommends the NG 2 (S/E) or NG 5/E power
        supply units. The connector is protected against reverse polarity.
      </div>

      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Read all instructions before use.</strong> Failure to follow
        the safety rules below may result in electric shock, fire, and/or
        serious injury. Use the tool only for its intended purpose, observing
        the general safety and accident-prevention regulations.
      </div>

      <h3>Work area and electrical safety</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Keep the work area clean, tidy, and well lit. Cluttered, dark areas invite accidents.</li>
        <li>Do not operate in explosive atmospheres (flammable liquids, gases, or dust) &mdash; power tools create sparks.</li>
        <li>Keep children and bystanders away while working.</li>
        <li>Never modify the plug or use adapter plugs with earthed tools. Avoid body contact with grounded surfaces (pipes, radiators, ranges, refrigerators).</li>
        <li>Do not expose the tool to rain or wet conditions.</li>
        <li>Do not abuse the cord &mdash; keep it away from heat, oil, sharp edges, and moving parts. Use an outdoor-rated extension cord outdoors.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Personal safety</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Stay alert; never operate while tired or under the influence of drugs, alcohol, or medication.</li>
        <li>Always wear eye protection. Use a dust mask, non-skid shoes, and hearing protection as appropriate.</li>
        <li>Ensure the switch is off before plugging in to avoid accidental starting. Never bridge the switch.</li>
        <li>Remove any adjusting key or wrench before switching on, and keep hands away from moving parts.</li>
        <li>Do not overreach &mdash; keep proper footing and balance.</li>
        <li>Dress properly: no loose clothing or jewellery; keep hair, clothing, and gloves away from moving parts.</li>
        <li>Where dust extraction connections are provided, ensure they are connected and used.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Use, care, and service</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Do not force the tool; use the correct tool for the application.</li>
        <li>Do not use the tool if the switch does not turn it on and off correctly.</li>
        <li>Disconnect from the power source before making adjustments, changing accessories, or storing.</li>
        <li>Store idle tools out of the reach of children and untrained users.</li>
        <li>Maintain the tool carefully; have a damaged tool repaired by a qualified expert before use.</li>
        <li>Secure the workpiece with clamps or a vice &mdash; this is safer and frees both hands.</li>
        <li>Have the tool serviced only by a qualified repair person using identical replacement parts. Check the mains lead regularly and have it replaced if damaged.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Description</h2>
      <p>
        The PS 13 is a superfine grinding device with a linear grinding
        surface, ideal for machining surfaces in recesses, slits,
        compartments, and small corners &mdash; in a nutshell, everywhere it is
        extremely tight. It ships with four grinding inserts (straight and
        angled) carrying variously formed surfaces, plus suitable self-adhesive
        sandpaper (waterproof) in grains 180, 240, and 400. Each sheet has
        5 &times; 4 different shapes pre-stamped, ready to peel and attach.
      </p>

      <h2>Working With the Device</h2>

      <h3>Mounting the grinding inserts</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Separate a grinding insert at its breaking point (arrow) from the
          carrier material.
          <div class="figure">
            <img src="/manuals/proxxon-ps13/fig1-separate-inserts.jpg" alt="Arrow pointing to the breaking point on the carrier frame where a grinding insert snaps free from the molded sprue" />
            <figcaption>Fig. 1 &mdash; snap the grinding insert free from the carrier at the breaking point (arrow)</figcaption>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          Turn the clamping mechanism (1) of the device 90&deg; to the left up
          to the limit stop, then push in the insert.
          <div class="figure">
            <img src="/manuals/proxxon-ps13/fig2-mount-insert.jpg" alt="PS 13 pen sander with the clamping mechanism rotated and a grinding insert being pushed into the head, with the clamping collar labeled 1" />
            <figcaption>Fig. 2 &mdash; turn the clamping mechanism (1) 90&deg; left to the stop and push in the insert, then turn it 90&deg; right to lock</figcaption>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>Turn the clamping mechanism (1) 90&deg; to the right again. The insert is now locked.</li>
        <li>
          Attach a suitable self-adhesive sandpaper shape, peeling it from the
          pre-stamped sheet and pressing it onto the insert.
          <div class="figure">
            <img src="/manuals/proxxon-ps13/fig3-attach-sandpaper.jpg" alt="Self-adhesive sandpaper shape being peeled from the pre-stamped sheet and pressed onto a flat grinding insert held in the PS 13 head" />
            <figcaption>Fig. 3 &mdash; press a self-adhesive sandpaper shape onto the mounted insert</figcaption>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Operation</h3>
      <p>
        Switch the device on and hold the pen sander like a ballpoint pen. The
        grinding movement (the stroke) goes from top to bottom and back again.
        Simply peel off and replace the sandpaper when it is worn.
      </p>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>For best results, work with only slight contact pressure</strong>
        so the grinding insert can vibrate freely. This makes the device as
        efficient as possible.
      </div>

      <h3>Typical applications</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/proxxon-ps13/applications.jpg" alt="Six line drawings of the PS 13 pen sander finishing tight areas: a corner, an edge, the inside of a round bowl, a narrow groove, a curved profile, and a recessed slot" />
        <figcaption>Typical applications for the PS 13 &mdash; finishing surfaces, edges, grooves, curves, and recesses where a larger sander cannot reach</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h2>Care and Maintenance</h2>
      <p>
        Apart from occasional cleaning, the device requires no special
        maintenance. If you observe the instructions in this manual, the device
        will give reliable, safe, and long-lasting service.
      </p>

